Different situation — on the EKS node you're outside the pod, so `localhost:9092` won't reach Kafka and the CLI tools aren't on the node. You've got two clean options.

**Option 1 (recommended): run the command inside the pod without a shell session.** You said you'd use `kubectl exec -it` — you don't need the interactive shell, just run the consumer directly through exec from the node:

```bash
kubectl exec $KAFKA_POD -n kafka -- \
  kafka-console-consumer.sh --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 \
  --topic <topic> --from-beginning --timeout-ms 15000 \
  --property print.partition=true --property print.offset=true \
  --property print.key=true --property print.timestamp=true \
  | grep -i '<search-string>'
```

Note: **drop the `-it` flags** when piping to `grep` — `-t` allocates a TTY and mangles the output for piping. Plain `kubectl exec` (no `-i`/`-t`) is correct here. The `grep` runs on the node, which is fine; only the consumer needs to run in the pod.

**Option 2: spin up a throwaway Kafka client pod** (if you'd rather not touch the broker pod, or it doesn't have the tools):

```bash
kubectl run kafka-client --rm -i --image=bitnami/kafka:latest -n kafka --restart=Never -- \
  kafka-console-consumer.sh \
  --bootstrap-server <bootstrap-service>:9092 \
  --topic <topic> --from-beginning --timeout-ms 15000 | grep -i '<search-string>'
```

Here you need the **in-cluster bootstrap address** (a Service DNS name like `kafka.kafka.svc.cluster.local:9092` or your MSK bootstrap brokers), not `localhost`, since this pod isn't the broker. `--rm` deletes it on exit.

To find the bootstrap service if you don't know it:

```bash
kubectl get svc -n kafka
kubectl get $KAFKA_POD -n kafka -o jsonpath='{.spec.containers[0].command}'   # sometimes shows the listener
```

Everything is still read-only (consuming with a throwaway group removes nothing and doesn't touch your real consumer offsets). The same bounding advice applies — add `--max-messages <n>` or `--offset -<N> --partition <p>` so a large topic doesn't stream millions of records.

